The paper discusses the continuous evolution of graphs and their applications in social networks, knowledge bases, and biological interactions. This suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of databases (cs.DB), social and information networks (cs.SI), and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also mentions applications such as news dissemination and content curation, which could fall under information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper presents experimental results using real-world and synthetic datasets, which could indicate a focus on computational social science (cs.SOC).
